{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658106","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658106"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:41:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:41:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20705"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20705","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20705"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13581"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95815"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13581"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20705"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78594"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11585"},{"type":"tags","id":"11782"},{"type":"tags","id":"12583"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32643"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32645"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95815"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ETissue repair involves a balance between synthesis and degradation of extracellular matrix (ECM) components. After initial deposition of connective tissue, the scar undergoes continuous modification through remodelling processes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the regulation of extracellular matrix remodelling during tissue repair?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Matrix metalloproteinases require calcium for enzymatic activity","Matrix metalloproteinases are secreted in permanently active forms","Matrix metalloproteinases are produced as inactive precursors","Matrix metalloproteinases are resistant to protein inhibitors","Matrix metalloproteinases degrade tissue inhibitor proteins"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that \u003Cstrong\u003EMatrix metalloproteinases are produced as inactive precursors\u003C/strong\u003E. MMPs are synthesised and secreted as inactive zymogens (pro-MMPs) that must be activated by proteases such as plasmin. This activation typically occurs only at sites of tissue injury, providing controlled ECM degradation during remodelling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMatrix metalloproteinases require calcium for enzymatic activity\u003C/strong\u003E - MMPs are zinc-dependent, not calcium-dependent enzymes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMatrix metalloproteinases are secreted in permanently active forms\u003C/strong\u003E - MMPs require specific activation to prevent inappropriate ECM degradation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMatrix metalloproteinases are resistant to protein inhibitors\u003C/strong\u003E - MMPs are regulated by tissue inhibitors of metalloproteinases (TIMPs)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMatrix metalloproteinases degrade tissue inhibitor proteins\u003C/strong\u003E - TIMPs inhibit MMPs, not vice versa\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe balance between MMP activation and inhibition by TIMPs is crucial for proper tissue remodelling and appropriate scar formation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Matrix metalloproteinases (MMPs) are zinc-dependent enzymes that degrade extracellular matrix components during tissue remodelling.","MMPs are produced as inactive zymogens that require activation by proteases such as plasmin.","Tissue inhibitors of metalloproteinases (TIMPs) regulate MMP activity to maintain balance between ECM synthesis and degradation."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 3, Inflammation and Repair; p. 107-108"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78594"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20705"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78594","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78594"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-29T20:34:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-29T20:35:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13581"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95815"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11585"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Inflammation and repair","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":2,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T15:14:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T15:14:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11782","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11782"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Overview of tissue repair","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-03-12T17:51:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-12T17:51:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12583"},"attribu